1
00:00:12,475 --> 00:00:18,421
Fasten your seatbelts and prepare to come along with me on a journey into this scrappy,

2
00:00:19,141 --> 00:00:25,968
unprofessional, chaotic and sometimes quite desperate adventure of solo indie game development.

3
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:32,205
Where there are no producers, no meetings, no one to delegate to, there is just you,

4
00:00:32,886 --> 00:00:36,569
your computer, and your determination to see it through to the end.

5
00:00:38,472 --> 00:00:41,815
So what is this talk going to be about?

6
00:00:42,196 --> 00:00:47,301
So it's going to be a, it's not just a level design talk.

7
00:00:47,822 --> 00:00:51,666
There's going to be a lot of explanation about how I built

8
00:00:51,706 --> 00:00:53,148
my first game, Hangline.

9
00:00:53,648 --> 00:00:57,232
So it's kind of like a post-mortem, but there is

10
00:00:57,272 --> 00:00:58,894
going to be a lot of level design information.

11
00:01:00,448 --> 00:01:13,963
So the reason I'm going to be talking about how I built my game and more about the game design and the creation and the structure of the game is because I think this is really fundamental into understanding the level design.

12
00:01:15,024 --> 00:01:17,187
As a solo indie game developer,

13
00:01:17,807 --> 00:01:21,352
You need to be able to not just be a level designer,

14
00:01:21,432 --> 00:01:23,414
you obviously need to be a programmer,

15
00:01:23,454 --> 00:01:24,736
you need to be a game designer,

16
00:01:25,436 --> 00:01:27,419
you need to be a producer, you need to be an artist,

17
00:01:27,439 --> 00:01:28,860
you basically need to be everything.

18
00:01:29,601 --> 00:01:32,104
So I think it's really important in explaining

19
00:01:32,144 --> 00:01:33,966
how I built the levels for the game

20
00:01:34,427 --> 00:01:37,210
to also explain a lot about the game design itself

21
00:01:37,370 --> 00:01:38,171
and the game creation.

22
00:01:40,642 --> 00:01:44,463
I'm going to be talking a lot about how to build a process

23
00:01:44,523 --> 00:01:46,344
for creating levels as quickly as possible,

24
00:01:46,744 --> 00:01:48,464
because that's something that was really important

25
00:01:48,484 --> 00:01:49,325
in making the game.

26
00:01:49,925 --> 00:01:54,006
And I'm also going to be talking about how to feed your levels

27
00:01:54,086 --> 00:01:56,087
to get them to stand out from each other

28
00:01:56,147 --> 00:01:59,088
and to be memorable in the player's mind.

29
00:01:59,748 --> 00:02:03,309
I'm going to be talking about how to teach game mechanics

30
00:02:03,889 --> 00:02:06,730
in an organic way, not just through forced tutorials.

31
00:02:07,691 --> 00:02:11,333
I'm also going to be talking about how to layer the systems of your game together

32
00:02:12,234 --> 00:02:19,178
so that you can get maximum variety out of very few game mechanics.

33
00:02:19,218 --> 00:02:22,941
Before I begin, I'm just going to show you a quick video of my game Hangline

34
00:02:23,041 --> 00:02:25,202
so you can understand a little bit about what it's about.

35
00:02:54,430 --> 00:02:55,372
All right, we're back.

36
00:02:55,532 --> 00:02:55,953
Excellent.

37
00:02:55,973 --> 00:02:58,115
Sorry about the technical difficulties there.

38
00:02:58,256 --> 00:03:00,459
Rule number one of giving a talk at GDC

39
00:03:00,539 --> 00:03:02,241
is don't use Google Slides.

40
00:03:03,803 --> 00:03:06,165
So I'm going to talk a little bit about myself now.

41
00:03:06,325 --> 00:03:10,328
So I spent a large amount of time in my career

42
00:03:10,368 --> 00:03:14,891
as a designer or lead designer on various AAA games,

43
00:03:15,592 --> 00:03:19,215
mostly games where you shoot people or blow things up.

44
00:03:19,735 --> 00:03:22,417
But at some point after being through quite

45
00:03:22,457 --> 00:03:24,379
a lot of different layoffs at different studios,

46
00:03:25,740 --> 00:03:28,422
and also the only projects being available

47
00:03:28,522 --> 00:03:29,363
were kind of, um...

48
00:03:30,442 --> 00:03:35,423
like a lot of sort of sequels, prequels, continuation of franchises,

49
00:03:36,384 --> 00:03:41,566
I started to think maybe I should try something different. And I started to think maybe I could

50
00:03:41,606 --> 00:03:47,508
go indie and try and build something by myself. But this is quite a scary thing.

51
00:03:48,808 --> 00:03:50,909
So the thing is making a game by yourself

52
00:03:52,430 --> 00:04:00,359
It's a very personal journey, and the way you navigate through that journey is very dependent on who you are as a person and your own shortcomings.

53
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,283
So not just your actual skills, but your personality as well.

54
00:04:05,565 --> 00:04:11,091
So I'm someone that worries a lot, and I'll think of like a thousand reasons why something isn't going to work.

55
00:04:12,352 --> 00:04:16,573
So even the idea of me making a game by myself was a terrifying thought,

56
00:04:17,813 --> 00:04:20,833
and obviously I thought of a lot of reasons why that is not going to work.

57
00:04:21,814 --> 00:04:25,314
And I needed a lot of pushing to even decide to do that.

58
00:04:26,354 --> 00:04:30,335
And for me, the push to do that, to become a solo indie developer,

59
00:04:30,715 --> 00:04:37,097
actually came from reading an article written by a fake robot dinosaur.

60
00:04:38,420 --> 00:04:40,842
So the article is called Win Like Stupid.

61
00:04:42,083 --> 00:04:47,747
And it's all about basically being a bit more stupid and

62
00:04:47,787 --> 00:04:50,689
being a bit more kind of not overthinking something and

63
00:04:51,049 --> 00:04:54,171
kind of moving ahead even though something may not seem

64
00:04:54,191 --> 00:04:55,052
like the greatest idea.

65
00:04:56,113 --> 00:05:00,616
So I can kind of show a little diagram from this article.

66
00:05:03,006 --> 00:05:10,493
And the important thing about this diagram is that the kind of intersection there between geniuses,

67
00:05:11,173 --> 00:05:16,758
so basically smart people, and like people that are winning in life and are successful,

68
00:05:17,138 --> 00:05:21,262
it's extremely small. And the kind of point of the article is all about

69
00:05:22,563 --> 00:05:25,385
being a little bit less judgmental of your own ideas.

70
00:05:26,686 --> 00:05:29,807
So the whole article is actually written in capitals

71
00:05:30,247 --> 00:05:32,667
because the sort of voice is meant to be

72
00:05:32,947 --> 00:05:33,908
like Grimlock's voice.

73
00:05:34,468 --> 00:05:37,008
So I'm gonna read you a few quotes from this article

74
00:05:37,248 --> 00:05:38,729
and in order to do it justice,

75
00:05:39,329 --> 00:05:41,009
I'm also gonna read them in the way

76
00:05:41,049 --> 00:05:43,950
that I expect they should be read, so.

77
00:05:46,290 --> 00:05:48,191
Smart people hate dumb ideas.

78
00:05:48,691 --> 00:05:51,331
Only think of ways idea can't win.

79
00:05:52,287 --> 00:05:55,487
Be too stupid for fear, too stupid to stop,

80
00:05:55,807 --> 00:05:57,948
too stupid to fail.

81
00:05:59,388 --> 00:06:01,009
And hopefully I haven't destroyed my voice

82
00:06:01,029 --> 00:06:01,989
for the rest of this talk now.

83
00:06:02,769 --> 00:06:04,369
So I think you get the point anyway.

84
00:06:04,449 --> 00:06:07,810
So this article was super useful in helping me actually

85
00:06:08,030 --> 00:06:08,850
start this journey.

86
00:06:09,730 --> 00:06:12,651
But there were significant hurdles

87
00:06:12,771 --> 00:06:15,132
to overcome upon doing this.

88
00:06:15,492 --> 00:06:19,473
So basically, when I started this path of solo indie game

89
00:06:21,430 --> 00:06:24,870
I had no team, and despite how much I kept going on

90
00:06:24,910 --> 00:06:26,351
about wise robot dinosaurs,

91
00:06:26,391 --> 00:06:27,851
no one really wanted to work with me.

92
00:06:29,031 --> 00:06:32,092
I had no funding, no money for contractors,

93
00:06:32,792 --> 00:06:35,653
no art skills, I'd not even built a 3D model in my life,

94
00:06:36,573 --> 00:06:38,133
and I had limited programming ability.

95
00:06:38,434 --> 00:06:40,514
The last time I programmed was at university.

96
00:06:41,234 --> 00:06:44,955
So, yeah, it doesn't seem like a great start, right?

97
00:06:45,435 --> 00:06:45,655
But...

98
00:06:46,489 --> 00:06:48,290
Gotta remember the words of the article.

99
00:06:48,850 --> 00:06:51,711
Be too stupid for fear, too stupid to stop,

100
00:06:51,991 --> 00:06:53,431
too stupid to fail.

101
00:06:54,111 --> 00:06:56,932
So, I went off and I started building this game.

102
00:06:57,572 --> 00:06:58,853
So that leads us to part one,

103
00:06:59,013 --> 00:07:00,873
which is building the concept itself.

104
00:07:02,694 --> 00:07:06,675
So, I left my job in San Francisco

105
00:07:06,855 --> 00:07:10,316
and I moved to Spain because I was kind of scared

106
00:07:10,336 --> 00:07:11,177
of the rent prices here

107
00:07:11,217 --> 00:07:12,617
and thought this would be a lot safer.

108
00:07:13,657 --> 00:07:14,678
And I constructed a plan.

109
00:07:16,476 --> 00:07:20,037
And that plan was to make a game in about three to six months,

110
00:07:20,117 --> 00:07:23,639
just do something super fast, super basic, get it done,

111
00:07:24,699 --> 00:07:27,860
fail miserably, and then do another one

112
00:07:27,900 --> 00:07:28,740
and make it much better.

113
00:07:28,760 --> 00:07:32,242
So yeah, what could possibly go wrong?

114
00:07:33,102 --> 00:07:34,763
The answer is many things.

115
00:07:35,863 --> 00:07:40,284
So I started to figure out some or put some goals down

116
00:07:40,304 --> 00:07:42,125
of what I wanted to try and achieve with this.

117
00:07:43,717 --> 00:07:46,378
So I thought, let's keep things very small,

118
00:07:46,798 --> 00:07:48,459
and I'll make a mobile game.

119
00:07:49,980 --> 00:07:52,640
Didn't want to get anything that was too crazy with scope.

120
00:07:52,700 --> 00:07:54,461
I thought, let's keep it really simple and small.

121
00:07:56,402 --> 00:07:58,102
I also thought I'd make a free-to-play game,

122
00:07:58,162 --> 00:07:59,623
because I had a little bit of experience

123
00:07:59,663 --> 00:08:03,144
at this, working at a small indie studio at one point.

124
00:08:05,108 --> 00:08:07,090
I also wanted to do something that was very,

125
00:08:07,110 --> 00:08:08,631
had a very relatable theme.

126
00:08:09,831 --> 00:08:12,293
So I didn't want anything fantasy or sci-fi.

127
00:08:12,313 --> 00:08:13,594
I wanted something very grounded,

128
00:08:14,234 --> 00:08:16,155
just to appeal to a wide audience.

129
00:08:17,376 --> 00:08:20,278
And I wanted very simple and easy to pick up controls.

130
00:08:21,158 --> 00:08:23,039
This was something that was really important to me.

131
00:08:24,684 --> 00:08:26,525
So I started writing ideas down,

132
00:08:27,185 --> 00:08:28,745
and the one that I was most excited about

133
00:08:28,845 --> 00:08:29,666
was a climbing game.

134
00:08:30,726 --> 00:08:33,507
So I thought to myself that the mobile controls,

135
00:08:33,888 --> 00:08:36,449
the touch screen, would be really effective

136
00:08:36,489 --> 00:08:37,429
for making a climbing game,

137
00:08:37,449 --> 00:08:38,590
because I thought you could kind of

138
00:08:39,070 --> 00:08:41,331
move the character's fingers with your thumbs,

139
00:08:42,051 --> 00:08:45,132
and sorry, move the character's arms with your thumbs,

140
00:08:45,332 --> 00:08:46,493
and kind of move around, and I was like,

141
00:08:46,533 --> 00:08:48,294
yeah, that'll work really well for a climbing game.

142
00:08:48,814 --> 00:08:51,915
But I thought, okay, let's do a little bit of research

143
00:08:52,055 --> 00:08:53,036
before I get going.

144
00:08:54,577 --> 00:08:58,359
And as it turns out, there was a lot of climbing games.

145
00:08:58,860 --> 00:09:01,162
Not only were there a lot of climbing games on mobile,

146
00:09:01,182 --> 00:09:02,583
there was even climbing games

147
00:09:02,603 --> 00:09:04,704
that used the exact same control system

148
00:09:04,764 --> 00:09:05,865
that I was excited about.

149
00:09:05,945 --> 00:09:09,468
So it was like, oh, okay, that's not a great start.

150
00:09:10,248 --> 00:09:13,611
But then I thought, what if you could just kind of

151
00:09:14,451 --> 00:09:15,732
give the guy a grappling hook?

152
00:09:16,784 --> 00:09:17,507
a lot more interesting.

153
00:09:25,648 --> 00:09:29,332
Most grappling hook games that were out at that time,

154
00:09:30,293 --> 00:09:31,214
they worked in a similar way,

155
00:09:31,334 --> 00:09:33,717
where you'd fire the grappling hook out,

156
00:09:34,537 --> 00:09:38,041
it would hit a solid barrier, you would swing,

157
00:09:38,221 --> 00:09:40,023
and then that barrier would also form

158
00:09:40,203 --> 00:09:42,205
like the kind of the shape of the level, right?

159
00:09:42,625 --> 00:09:43,907
So everything's kind of very,

160
00:09:44,948 --> 00:09:46,830
kind of rigid 2D physics, let's say.

161
00:09:47,791 --> 00:09:50,612
And the idea I had, or the twist on it, let's say,

162
00:09:51,052 --> 00:09:52,733
is that I thought it would be really cool

163
00:09:52,793 --> 00:09:56,876
is if you could just literally click anywhere on the screen

164
00:09:57,416 --> 00:09:59,997
and send the grappling hook out to that point.

165
00:10:00,037 --> 00:10:01,398
So you don't have to connect it

166
00:10:01,438 --> 00:10:02,879
to a specific bit of collision.

167
00:10:03,960 --> 00:10:06,401
And that way, you know, you would swing out

168
00:10:06,481 --> 00:10:09,583
and it would give a lot more sort of finesse

169
00:10:09,683 --> 00:10:10,563
to the controls.

170
00:10:11,724 --> 00:10:13,125
And this seems like a simple idea,

171
00:10:13,205 --> 00:10:15,566
but basically the entire game is built around this.

172
00:10:17,264 --> 00:10:22,209
So I set off and I thought, okay, first thing we need to do is prototype it.

173
00:10:22,269 --> 00:10:27,234
Obviously, you know, the first time you do everything, it's probably going to be a failure,

174
00:10:27,254 --> 00:10:31,538
so you may as well test it out first. This is me testing out this exact GDC talk.

175
00:10:32,098 --> 00:10:35,722
So I'm a pretty lazy programmer, basically.

176
00:10:36,701 --> 00:10:39,963
I don't really want to program anything unless I absolutely have to.

177
00:10:40,363 --> 00:10:44,866
So the very first thing I did was I looked on the Unity Asset Store,

178
00:10:45,226 --> 00:10:49,389
just in case there was something which I could use for swinging you up a mountain.

179
00:10:50,490 --> 00:10:54,892
Lo and behold, I found Easy 2D Grappling Hook for a mere $10.

180
00:10:55,072 --> 00:10:59,335
And it turned out this was the best $10 I've ever spent.

181
00:11:00,912 --> 00:11:07,016
So I got this going and before only a few days,

182
00:11:07,076 --> 00:11:10,339
I managed to get a kind of Unity cube swinging about.

183
00:11:12,080 --> 00:11:13,721
And this was already starting to look like,

184
00:11:13,921 --> 00:11:14,802
you know, this could work.

185
00:11:15,743 --> 00:11:15,883
So.

186
00:11:16,883 --> 00:11:20,405
I started to think, okay, what is the actual point of the levels?

187
00:11:20,485 --> 00:11:22,185
Like, how are things gonna work here?

188
00:11:22,245 --> 00:11:23,046
What's the structure?

189
00:11:24,066 --> 00:11:26,026
So I just kept with something very simple.

190
00:11:26,367 --> 00:11:27,887
You start at the bottom of the mountain.

191
00:11:28,847 --> 00:11:30,348
You have to navigate your way through,

192
00:11:30,888 --> 00:11:33,809
and there'll be some pickups on the way, stars,

193
00:11:34,729 --> 00:11:37,770
and then you have to get to the top and hit the flag,

194
00:11:38,090 --> 00:11:38,951
and that's the end of the level.

195
00:11:39,929 --> 00:11:40,769
So this was my plan.

196
00:11:42,010 --> 00:11:46,414
Now, there were some first steps I needed to take here.

197
00:11:46,514 --> 00:11:50,016
So obviously, I needed some barriers in the environment

198
00:11:50,076 --> 00:11:53,199
to slow you down and to form the shape of the level.

199
00:11:54,020 --> 00:11:56,522
And I need some hazards to avoid to make

200
00:11:56,542 --> 00:11:57,883
it a bit more of a challenge.

201
00:11:59,324 --> 00:12:01,225
But the other thing was I needed to make the grapple

202
00:12:01,245 --> 00:12:04,628
a little bit more elastic and springy to fit the kind of feel

203
00:12:04,648 --> 00:12:05,429
that I was looking for.

204
00:12:06,310 --> 00:12:07,932
So next prototype.

205
00:12:08,813 --> 00:12:13,377
So here you can see these Unity cubes scaled up and down.

206
00:12:13,397 --> 00:12:15,058
That's the gray boxes there.

207
00:12:16,079 --> 00:12:18,581
The grapple is a little bit more elastic.

208
00:12:19,102 --> 00:12:20,543
And then as you're swinging around,

209
00:12:20,823 --> 00:12:22,365
you've got some of these red blocks

210
00:12:22,385 --> 00:12:23,726
that basically kill you instantly.

211
00:12:25,236 --> 00:12:28,639
So this provided a few initial discoveries.

212
00:12:29,119 --> 00:12:30,520
Swinging around was really good fun.

213
00:12:32,681 --> 00:12:35,483
But it was very hard to be precise with the physics.

214
00:12:36,344 --> 00:12:39,946
So the thing about physics is that it gives a lot of free

215
00:12:40,006 --> 00:12:43,729
gameplay, like it has this unpredictability, which

216
00:12:43,809 --> 00:12:45,690
creates a lot of emerging gameplay.

217
00:12:46,110 --> 00:12:49,332
But the problem is that unpredictability can also lead

218
00:12:49,372 --> 00:12:52,314
to frustration if you punish the player really severely.

219
00:12:52,896 --> 00:12:56,375
So basically anything that instantly killed you was not such a good idea.

220
00:12:58,449 --> 00:13:03,472
The other thing that this prototype taught me was that level design is basically everything in this game.

221
00:13:04,452 --> 00:13:10,956
It's super duper important and the game is basically going to live or die based on the level design.

222
00:13:12,356 --> 00:13:16,078
So the next thing I did was whack in a character into the game.

223
00:13:16,358 --> 00:13:19,140
This was just some guy I'd made in a Blender tutorial.

224
00:13:19,820 --> 00:13:22,942
He wasn't massively happy about being in the game, but he didn't really have a choice.

225
00:13:24,243 --> 00:13:26,645
And so I thought, let's make some hazards

226
00:13:26,745 --> 00:13:28,747
that don't insta-kill the player.

227
00:13:29,668 --> 00:13:33,071
So the first of those was this kind of a falling snow panel.

228
00:13:33,271 --> 00:13:36,294
Obviously here, it's just, again, a Unity cube.

229
00:13:36,815 --> 00:13:39,537
But this kind of pulled you out your way,

230
00:13:39,637 --> 00:13:41,819
and then it didn't kill you instantly,

231
00:13:41,919 --> 00:13:43,020
but it put you into danger,

232
00:13:43,081 --> 00:13:44,862
and you had to quickly react to get out of there.

233
00:13:46,404 --> 00:13:51,630
So another sort of non-instakill hazard was this falling block.

234
00:13:52,211 --> 00:14:03,785
Similar kind of idea except this was a solid block that could actually crush you if it landed on top of you either too fast or if it crushed you against a sort of solid ground piece.

235
00:14:05,397 --> 00:14:09,644
I also whacked in an avalanche because obviously this is a game about climbing mountains and

236
00:14:09,704 --> 00:14:11,186
that seemed pretty appropriate.

237
00:14:12,267 --> 00:14:15,693
So there's a bunch of things that I put in there that sort of knock you off the line,

238
00:14:15,893 --> 00:14:16,854
but they didn't kill you.

239
00:14:16,954 --> 00:14:20,500
So you still had some moments to react and continue playing.

240
00:14:22,297 --> 00:14:27,323
Now, around this point, I started to think about marketing and sort of getting the word of the game out there.

241
00:14:28,324 --> 00:14:35,051
And I met a chap who worked for a Spanish magazine at a game conference,

242
00:14:35,131 --> 00:14:37,734
and then I was talking about my game, and then he was like,

243
00:14:37,794 --> 00:14:39,736
oh yeah, let me know when it's something to look at.

244
00:14:40,557 --> 00:14:42,278
And then at one point I sent him an email.

245
00:14:43,159 --> 00:14:44,540
And I've got the email right here.

246
00:14:44,761 --> 00:14:48,384
So this was the first point where I was trying to describe,

247
00:14:48,464 --> 00:14:51,406
like, what is the game in one sentence, you know?

248
00:14:51,586 --> 00:14:54,569
So I came up with this super quick tagline of,

249
00:14:54,649 --> 00:14:56,110
you're a dude with a grappling hook,

250
00:14:56,610 --> 00:14:58,692
and you have to swing your way up to the top of the mountain,

251
00:14:58,812 --> 00:15:02,095
dodging falling rocks, avalanches, and angry mountain goats.

252
00:15:02,615 --> 00:15:04,457
Thought, yeah, that sounds pretty cool.

253
00:15:05,949 --> 00:15:07,572
Then he emails me back saying,

254
00:15:07,913 --> 00:15:10,137
that line, angry mountain goats, really got me.

255
00:15:10,758 --> 00:15:11,399
Smiley face.

256
00:15:11,419 --> 00:15:15,166
I was like, oh, yeah, I don't actually have goats

257
00:15:15,247 --> 00:15:18,713
in the game and I have no idea how they're gonna work.

258
00:15:19,807 --> 00:15:21,268
But I guess I've got to put them in now.

259
00:15:21,428 --> 00:15:25,851
So I built a goat using Unity cubes, obviously.

260
00:15:26,551 --> 00:15:28,032
You know, as you can see,

261
00:15:28,172 --> 00:15:30,073
artistic skills at this point were not great.

262
00:15:31,034 --> 00:15:32,595
And I was like, well, what's a goat going to do?

263
00:15:32,615 --> 00:15:35,037
I mean, probably he's going to kick you, right?

264
00:15:35,117 --> 00:15:37,178
So, okay, let's put a trigger on it,

265
00:15:37,779 --> 00:15:40,060
and we'll get him to fire an impulse as soon as you go near.

266
00:15:41,021 --> 00:15:43,723
So I slapped it in there,

267
00:15:44,103 --> 00:15:47,605
and once he actually gets to the mountain...

268
00:15:50,539 --> 00:15:52,401
Boom, get smacked by the goat.

269
00:15:52,882 --> 00:15:56,426
And miraculously, everyone that played the game

