00:15:56,847 --> 00:15:58,449
absolutely loved the goats.

271
00:15:58,749 --> 00:16:01,532
And even all the way to the end of the game,

272
00:16:01,572 --> 00:16:03,294
this was the thing that everyone seemed to comment on.

273
00:16:03,695 --> 00:16:06,438
So if you don't take away anything else from this talk,

274
00:16:06,538 --> 00:16:08,240
just basically put goats in your game.

275
00:16:10,070 --> 00:16:13,993
So next thing I decided to do was test on the target platform.

276
00:16:14,233 --> 00:16:16,715
So I built a mobile build as quickly as possible.

277
00:16:17,996 --> 00:16:20,899
This came with a few discoveries.

278
00:16:21,559 --> 00:16:23,781
It's very hard to see what's ahead

279
00:16:24,322 --> 00:16:26,984
because you've got this kind of narrow field of view.

280
00:16:29,026 --> 00:16:32,408
So basically, it was very easy to kind of smash into stuff

281
00:16:32,508 --> 00:16:33,829
if you were moving left to right,

282
00:16:34,590 --> 00:16:36,051
because you couldn't see too far ahead.

283
00:16:37,151 --> 00:16:40,914
So basically, yeah, moving very fast, left or right directly,

284
00:16:41,334 --> 00:16:43,196
was not good in the levels.

285
00:16:43,916 --> 00:16:47,219
So basically, the levels needed more diagonal motion.

286
00:16:48,380 --> 00:16:50,741
So to kind of explain this a little bit better,

287
00:16:52,346 --> 00:16:53,708
I've got this crude diagram here.

288
00:16:53,788 --> 00:16:57,251
So imagine you're sending out your grappling hook

289
00:16:57,351 --> 00:16:59,053
to the red dot there.

290
00:17:00,414 --> 00:17:03,917
What this is gonna do is kind of swing you in an arc, right?

291
00:17:04,478 --> 00:17:06,920
So then we fire out our next grappling hook.

292
00:17:07,741 --> 00:17:10,442
And then we're going to kind of swing back around.

293
00:17:10,482 --> 00:17:13,182
So imagine we're kind of trying to move up the screen here.

294
00:17:14,503 --> 00:17:15,563
And we fire another one out.

295
00:17:15,763 --> 00:17:17,683
And then we're swinging in the other direction.

296
00:17:18,064 --> 00:17:21,344
So essentially, you're kind of making curves as you move.

297
00:17:22,825 --> 00:17:26,566
And basically, I realized this is kind of like a driving game.

298
00:17:27,326 --> 00:17:29,206
So in a driving game, the cars are

299
00:17:30,199 --> 00:17:31,379
are physics-based, right?

300
00:17:31,799 --> 00:17:35,601
And you're controlling them, but they're also moving a lot

301
00:17:35,681 --> 00:17:37,121
by the physics of the world.

302
00:17:38,102 --> 00:17:41,143
And your racetracks are very smooth and curvy

303
00:17:41,223 --> 00:17:42,103
because of that, right?

304
00:17:42,143 --> 00:17:44,024
They're not just flat, straight lines.

305
00:17:45,204 --> 00:17:47,245
So basically, this made me realize

306
00:17:47,345 --> 00:17:50,747
that for an ideal-shaped level, I'm

307
00:17:50,927 --> 00:17:53,107
going to need some sweeping curves.

308
00:17:53,568 --> 00:17:56,909
I'm going to need more organic shapes, right?

309
00:17:58,562 --> 00:17:59,883
How the heck am I going to do this

310
00:18:00,043 --> 00:18:02,044
if everything is made from Unity cubes?

311
00:18:02,765 --> 00:18:05,046
So, like, this was what the levels were at that point.

312
00:18:05,086 --> 00:18:07,507
It's all, you know, really straight lines, right?

313
00:18:08,007 --> 00:18:12,070
So, this moves us neatly on to part two,

314
00:18:12,250 --> 00:18:13,270
which is pre-production,

315
00:18:13,711 --> 00:18:16,492
basically how to actually build these levels.

316
00:18:17,353 --> 00:18:18,573
So, at this point, I was thinking,

317
00:18:19,054 --> 00:18:20,234
I need to get into Blender

318
00:18:20,474 --> 00:18:23,136
and start, you know, actually building a level properly.

319
00:18:25,188 --> 00:18:33,215
But what I decided to do is find a way to take my crappy Unity cube levels and put them into Blender.

320
00:18:34,076 --> 00:18:39,821
So I looked on the internet and I found this tool that was an OBJ exporter for Unity.

321
00:18:40,542 --> 00:18:47,408
So this allowed me to take my basic, basic cube levels, take them out of Unity, put them into Blender.

322
00:18:48,189 --> 00:18:50,350
play around with them, make them look a bit better,

323
00:18:50,490 --> 00:18:52,411
and then pull them back into Unity

324
00:18:52,471 --> 00:18:53,852
and they'd have all the same collision.

325
00:18:53,872 --> 00:18:55,693
So that's what I did.

326
00:18:55,713 --> 00:18:58,254
And this was kind of what I ended up with there,

327
00:18:59,035 --> 00:19:00,555
which was, it was okay.

328
00:19:00,676 --> 00:19:02,056
Starting to look a little bit better.

329
00:19:02,076 --> 00:19:03,857
It looks a little bit more like a mountain now.

330
00:19:05,378 --> 00:19:06,439
But I discovered...

331
00:19:07,383 --> 00:19:09,905
The building level art is really slow.

332
00:19:09,925 --> 00:19:14,429
So just to kind of get an idea of what I mean by slow,

333
00:19:15,229 --> 00:19:18,412
so my goal for playing a level was that it should take

334
00:19:18,452 --> 00:19:19,473
about three minutes.

335
00:19:19,613 --> 00:19:21,355
This was like a rough approximation

336
00:19:22,275 --> 00:19:23,356
when you're actually playing it.

337
00:19:23,837 --> 00:19:27,880
So I was trying to make about like five hours of gameplay

338
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:29,481
for the first release of this game,

339
00:19:30,182 --> 00:19:32,004
just so people would have enough to play

340
00:19:32,044 --> 00:19:33,885
and they'd watch some ads and I would hopefully

341
00:19:33,925 --> 00:19:34,406
make some money.

342
00:19:36,080 --> 00:19:39,543
So if we times five hours by 60 minutes per hour,

343
00:19:39,583 --> 00:19:41,425
we get some other number,

344
00:19:41,465 --> 00:19:43,006
and then we divide that by three minutes,

345
00:19:43,286 --> 00:19:44,787
and we get 100 levels.

346
00:19:44,988 --> 00:19:48,330
That is what I would need for five hours of gameplay.

347
00:19:50,112 --> 00:19:52,754
But really, probably more like 50 levels, right?

348
00:19:52,774 --> 00:19:54,615
Because the player is going to die occasionally,

349
00:19:54,816 --> 00:19:56,937
and we don't need them to, you know,

350
00:19:56,977 --> 00:19:59,279
well, they're not going to just play through every level

351
00:19:59,640 --> 00:20:00,120
one after the other.

352
00:20:01,315 --> 00:20:04,037
But this was like, literally it was taking me five days

353
00:20:04,097 --> 00:20:06,879
to build a level because of my crappy 3D art skills

354
00:20:06,939 --> 00:20:10,281
and because this was just a really slow process.

355
00:20:10,362 --> 00:20:12,583
So obviously five days to build a level,

356
00:20:13,804 --> 00:20:17,006
you've got like 250 working days to finish this game,

357
00:20:17,066 --> 00:20:18,807
like just the levels.

358
00:20:18,987 --> 00:20:21,069
So this was not feasible.

359
00:20:21,789 --> 00:20:23,330
And I started to think like,

360
00:20:23,470 --> 00:20:25,592
what other solutions are there for solving this?

361
00:20:26,953 --> 00:20:27,593
And then I thought.

362
00:20:28,730 --> 00:20:32,232
Maybe I could generate the art automatically.

363
00:20:36,414 --> 00:20:38,074
Automatic mesh generation.

364
00:20:38,455 --> 00:20:40,736
So I started mentioning this to friends

365
00:20:40,756 --> 00:20:42,016
and they were like, are you mad?

366
00:20:42,717 --> 00:20:43,497
What the hell?

367
00:20:43,857 --> 00:20:45,738
That's for serious programmers, not noobs.

368
00:20:47,459 --> 00:20:49,020
This idea is dumb.

369
00:20:49,120 --> 00:20:51,421
And I was thinking, yeah, this idea is really dumb.

370
00:20:52,255 --> 00:20:55,076
But then I remembered the words of that wise robot dinosaur,

371
00:20:55,656 --> 00:20:57,577
smart people hate dumb ideas.

372
00:20:57,918 --> 00:21:00,559
Only think of ways idea can't win.

373
00:21:00,579 --> 00:21:02,860
And I thought, okay, let's try this.

374
00:21:03,840 --> 00:21:06,002
So again, I went on the internet

375
00:21:06,102 --> 00:21:07,482
and searched for something that might help.

376
00:21:08,083 --> 00:21:10,144
And I found this tool called PolyMesh.

377
00:21:10,844 --> 00:21:14,046
So this is a tool that allows you to basically,

378
00:21:14,246 --> 00:21:17,327
in the Unity editor, set up points

379
00:21:17,407 --> 00:21:19,348
for creating simple 2D collision.

380
00:21:20,381 --> 00:21:23,583
So I thought the plan was I could use this to kind of build

381
00:21:23,643 --> 00:21:26,004
the shape of the level directly in the editor

382
00:21:26,084 --> 00:21:27,365
and get a more organic shape.

383
00:21:28,606 --> 00:21:30,407
So it also allowed you to kind of like,

384
00:21:30,467 --> 00:21:32,648
as you plotted the points out, it would make the collision

385
00:21:32,688 --> 00:21:36,530
and it would also kind of bevel or sort of extrude

386
00:21:36,550 --> 00:21:37,871
the edges to make a shape.

387
00:21:39,191 --> 00:21:41,572
So I started working on this, got it integrated,

388
00:21:41,952 --> 00:21:45,132
got it together, and this was a massive step forwards.

389
00:21:45,973 --> 00:21:48,493
I could then build levels that were a lot more

390
00:21:48,533 --> 00:21:49,533
interestingly shaped.

391
00:21:50,674 --> 00:21:53,194
So here you can see I've also got kind of a separation

392
00:21:53,254 --> 00:21:56,935
between the back wall, which is like this snowy area,

393
00:21:57,695 --> 00:21:59,155
which you can grapple and connect to.

394
00:21:59,595 --> 00:22:02,376
And then there's also the solid gray rocks,

395
00:22:03,136 --> 00:22:06,517
and sort of like a solid kind of front wall of rock

396
00:22:06,557 --> 00:22:07,477
that you couldn't get past.

397
00:22:09,118 --> 00:22:14,943
So this was a huge help, but it's still not looking that amazing yet, right?

398
00:22:15,384 --> 00:22:16,125
It's quite basic.

399
00:22:17,266 --> 00:22:23,531
So the next part of this step was figuring out, like, can I actually deform those meshes

400
00:22:23,711 --> 00:22:25,173
to make them look a bit more interesting?

401
00:22:26,874 --> 00:22:31,538
And again, I went on the Internet and started looking to see if there was some code I could use.

402
00:22:32,542 --> 00:22:36,584
And I found this package called Coherent Noise Generation.

403
00:22:36,924 --> 00:22:38,985
And this had lots of different noise curves

404
00:22:39,025 --> 00:22:40,546
that you could apply to meshes.

405
00:22:41,206 --> 00:22:42,507
So I started fiddling around with it,

406
00:22:43,388 --> 00:22:47,690
and I managed to start manipulating some meshes

407
00:22:48,350 --> 00:22:49,731
to make some interesting shapes.

408
00:22:50,872 --> 00:22:54,354
And to cut a long story short, I came up with a process

409
00:22:54,614 --> 00:22:58,977
to build more interesting looking rocks and level shapes.

410
00:22:59,057 --> 00:23:02,139
So this is kind of a top level summary of it.

411
00:23:02,839 --> 00:23:06,761
Basically, I used the PolyMesh tool to shape the rocks.

412
00:23:07,702 --> 00:23:11,184
Then I used another tool to triangulate them.

413
00:23:11,744 --> 00:23:13,726
So this is about basically making

414
00:23:13,806 --> 00:23:17,348
the mesh into lots of reasonably evenly shaped triangles,

415
00:23:17,368 --> 00:23:18,629
because that's really important when you

416
00:23:18,649 --> 00:23:19,709
want to try and deform them.

417
00:23:20,910 --> 00:23:23,951
Then I would add depth to that shape and pull it out.

418
00:23:24,951 --> 00:23:30,973
Then I would apply the coherent noise algorithm

419
00:23:31,173 --> 00:23:33,634
to deform it with a Voronoi curve.

420
00:23:33,874 --> 00:23:35,834
So this kind of makes cells, and that's

421
00:23:35,874 --> 00:23:37,795
why you get these sort of little rock shapes.

422
00:23:38,955 --> 00:23:42,376
Then I would make the vertices all the same for each triangle

423
00:23:42,456 --> 00:23:45,637
to make flat shading, because I wanted the low poly look.

424
00:23:46,867 --> 00:23:50,808
Then I would simplify that using a decimator tool.

425
00:23:50,888 --> 00:23:52,729
Again, some code that I found on the internet.

426
00:23:52,889 --> 00:23:54,850
It was all free and all legitimate, I promise.

427
00:23:55,391 --> 00:23:57,412
And then for the last part,

428
00:23:59,224 --> 00:24:03,667
I would basically check if the triangle is facing upwards,

429
00:24:04,148 --> 00:24:06,129
or roughly upwards, and then color it white.

430
00:24:07,030 --> 00:24:08,471
I don't know why I've written snow shader there.

431
00:24:08,491 --> 00:24:10,052
That was probably to sound more intelligent,

432
00:24:10,072 --> 00:24:11,873
because at this point I had no idea what a shader was.

433
00:24:13,174 --> 00:24:16,136
Okay, so this is basically what this looks like.

434
00:24:16,957 --> 00:24:20,580
We've got our 2D simple shape for the collision of the level,

435
00:24:21,380 --> 00:24:24,423
and it would deform it into this more interesting-looking rock.

436
00:24:25,447 --> 00:24:30,451
And there is a GIF right here which shows it working.

437
00:24:30,531 --> 00:24:34,074
So that's me kind of sculpting, pulling out the points

438
00:24:34,234 --> 00:24:38,258
to make this more organically shaped rock collision.

439
00:24:39,759 --> 00:24:44,483
And then after a few seconds of my computer wearing its fans

440
00:24:44,563 --> 00:24:46,104
and doing all these calculations,

441
00:24:46,905 --> 00:24:49,948
it would eventually create a more interesting looking rock.

442
00:24:49,968 --> 00:24:52,870
Yeah.

443
00:24:53,070 --> 00:24:53,270
So.

444
00:24:55,020 --> 00:24:59,783
This was a massive improvement, and with a bit of lighting and some post-processing,

445
00:25:00,263 --> 00:25:04,185
the levels now, to me, looked good enough for production.

446
00:25:05,786 --> 00:25:07,527
So this changed everything, basically.

447
00:25:08,748 --> 00:25:11,970
It allowed me to rapidly experiment and try lots of ideas out.

448
00:25:12,991 --> 00:25:17,273
It created much more organic-feeling levels, or it allowed me to create more organic-feeling

449
00:25:17,293 --> 00:25:17,553
levels.

450
00:25:18,844 --> 00:25:21,425
And it also allowed me to create more variety

451
00:25:21,465 --> 00:25:24,267
in the obstacles, because I had a lot of falling rocks

452
00:25:24,387 --> 00:25:26,989
and things like that, which I could now custom

453
00:25:27,029 --> 00:25:29,851
build the shapes for, which was a huge, huge improvement.

454
00:25:31,112 --> 00:25:34,434
And basically, with this tool, I could build a level from,

455
00:25:34,495 --> 00:25:36,516
whoa, this is scary, what the heck?

456
00:25:38,477 --> 00:25:40,359
Okay, I guess we'll just keep going.

457
00:25:40,519 --> 00:25:43,261
I could build a level from zero to done in four hours,

458
00:25:43,381 --> 00:25:46,043
which was a massive improvement from what we had before.

459
00:25:47,571 --> 00:25:52,813
So yeah, basically, if we recalculate how long it would take to build 50 levels, it's more like about 25 days.

460
00:25:52,833 --> 00:25:54,574
So this was massive.

461
00:25:56,735 --> 00:26:03,418
So the next thing I want to talk about, because it really relates to the level design, is the layering of game mechanics.

462
00:26:06,156 --> 00:26:10,720
So at this point, I had kind of like made the mechanics

463
00:26:10,760 --> 00:26:12,061
sort of in isolation, right?

464
00:26:12,141 --> 00:26:14,604
So yeah, if you can kind of, you know,

465
00:26:14,644 --> 00:26:16,786
playing the game and you encounter one mechanic on its own,

466
00:26:16,826 --> 00:26:17,626
that's cool.

467
00:26:18,207 --> 00:26:20,949
But if we have several mechanics that interplay together

468
00:26:21,070 --> 00:26:22,050
and connect together,

469
00:26:23,392 --> 00:26:24,713
that's gonna be a lot more interesting.

470
00:26:25,848 --> 00:26:29,470
So we're going to get slightly programmer-y for a second here,

471
00:26:29,510 --> 00:26:31,110
but I assure you it's quite basic.

472
00:26:31,971 --> 00:26:35,052
So this is the object hierarchy diagram for the game.

473
00:26:35,852 --> 00:26:38,594
And I really feel like the whole electricity

474
00:26:38,614 --> 00:26:39,334
is going to go off soon.

475
00:26:39,354 --> 00:26:41,935
I need to finish this talk before disaster happens.

476
00:26:43,116 --> 00:26:48,781
So here, as an example, I wanted the goats to do more than just kick the player.

477
00:26:48,801 --> 00:26:50,823
I wanted them to kick other things too.

478
00:26:51,463 --> 00:26:58,270
So I made this behavior of kicking happen on a destructible object,

479
00:26:58,330 --> 00:27:00,051
which is at the top of the hierarchy there.

480
00:27:00,652 --> 00:27:02,992
And so everything under destructible objects

