00:27:03,152 --> 00:27:05,673
also can do whatever a destructible object does.

482
00:27:06,153 --> 00:27:09,354
So because the goat could then kick a destructible object,

483
00:27:09,534 --> 00:27:11,794
it meant that it could also kick dynamite,

484
00:27:12,274 --> 00:27:14,735
it could kick mountain cats, it could kick the player,

485
00:27:14,995 --> 00:27:17,376
and a goat could even kick other goats.

486
00:27:17,856 --> 00:27:21,357
And this created a lot more interesting possibilities

487
00:27:21,397 --> 00:27:22,757
with combining the mechanics.

488
00:27:24,018 --> 00:27:26,739
So as you can see here, the cat jumps on the player,

489
00:27:26,759 --> 00:27:29,561
the cat gets kicked by the goat, the goat falls on...

490
00:27:29,701 --> 00:27:32,082
Yeah, okay, anyway, you can see basically

491
00:27:32,202 --> 00:27:34,283
lots of cool stuff happens that's quite interesting

492
00:27:34,303 --> 00:27:34,964
and unpredictable.

493
00:27:35,804 --> 00:27:38,125
So that was a massive help in allowing me

494
00:27:38,205 --> 00:27:40,887
to layer the mechanics together in the levels.

495
00:27:42,608 --> 00:27:45,749
All right, so I knew how to make the levels

496
00:27:45,789 --> 00:27:47,130
and what the process was gonna be.

497
00:27:47,490 --> 00:27:49,632
So the next thing I needed to do was figure out

498
00:27:49,732 --> 00:27:51,352
how to make them actually play well.

499
00:27:52,896 --> 00:27:57,257
So I was, yeah, the next part was, yeah, basically what makes a good level?

500
00:27:58,537 --> 00:28:02,058
So there's kind of three basic things I'm going to talk about here.

501
00:28:02,318 --> 00:28:04,399
So the one is, first one is tutorials.

502
00:28:04,539 --> 00:28:07,260
So that's explaining these game mechanics to the player.

503
00:28:07,860 --> 00:28:12,801
And I didn't want to do a scripted kind of stop the player and make them

504
00:28:13,181 --> 00:28:15,022
read a tutorial message at all.

505
00:28:15,182 --> 00:28:19,003
I wanted to make it much more organic and in the level.

506
00:28:19,303 --> 00:28:20,903
And I'm going to talk about that in a sec.

507
00:28:22,584 --> 00:28:27,427
Also, I found that variety was a really important thing in making the levels interesting.

508
00:28:28,347 --> 00:28:32,670
And there's a lot of different aspects to that, which I'll talk about in a moment.

509
00:28:34,066 --> 00:28:35,747
And also theming was really important.

510
00:28:36,047 --> 00:28:38,227
So that's making the levels stand out from each other

511
00:28:38,607 --> 00:28:40,268
and being each one of them being memorable

512
00:28:40,548 --> 00:28:41,368
in the player's mind.

513
00:28:42,108 --> 00:28:44,049
So let's get into detail on these.

514
00:28:44,629 --> 00:28:47,370
So the tutorials, as I said,

515
00:28:47,410 --> 00:28:50,331
I wanted to not do guided tutorials.

516
00:28:50,391 --> 00:28:52,392
I wanted the player to learn organically

517
00:28:52,492 --> 00:28:56,993
by doing the thing that kind of shows the mechanic,

518
00:28:57,273 --> 00:28:59,974
kind of a bit more Nintendo design philosophy, I guess.

519
00:29:01,515 --> 00:29:06,540
So I had a dedicated level that would show you how to,

520
00:29:06,560 --> 00:29:09,903
or kind of force you to experience the mechanic.

521
00:29:10,523 --> 00:29:12,785
And then what I would do is reinforce that mechanic

522
00:29:12,926 --> 00:29:13,826
in the next few levels.

523
00:29:15,159 --> 00:29:17,581
And then I will show the breadth of that mechanic afterwards.

524
00:29:17,822 --> 00:29:20,304
So that means layering it with other mechanics

525
00:29:20,384 --> 00:29:22,966
to show how it also fits into everything else.

526
00:29:24,007 --> 00:29:26,809
So let's dive into a simple example.

527
00:29:27,730 --> 00:29:29,312
So here we've got the goats.

528
00:29:29,372 --> 00:29:31,494
This is the first level where you encounter a goat.

529
00:29:32,014 --> 00:29:34,256
And the player starts at the bottom left of the level.

530
00:29:34,957 --> 00:29:37,459
And they have really no choice but to go

531
00:29:37,479 --> 00:29:39,321
through this quite tight gap here.

532
00:29:40,522 --> 00:29:43,565
And on going through that tight gap, they see this cute little goat.

533
00:29:43,805 --> 00:29:45,066
They don't really think much of it.

534
00:29:45,487 --> 00:29:48,190
They will naturally accidentally swing into the goat,

535
00:29:48,270 --> 00:29:49,591
and the goat will kick them in the face.

536
00:29:50,312 --> 00:29:51,413
And they will be quite angry,

537
00:29:51,733 --> 00:29:54,596
but they will also understand exactly what a goat does.

538
00:29:56,108 --> 00:29:59,632
Then, if we look at the rest of the level, zoomed out,

539
00:30:00,873 --> 00:30:03,916
just in case the player misses that first goat somehow,

540
00:30:04,376 --> 00:30:08,500
there is basically a goat on every single tight gap

541
00:30:08,560 --> 00:30:09,341
in the entire level.

542
00:30:09,541 --> 00:30:11,623
So by the end of it, they're basically swearing

543
00:30:11,703 --> 00:30:13,325
because they got kicked by a goat so many times,

544
00:30:13,365 --> 00:30:14,666
but they understand how they work.

545
00:30:16,290 --> 00:30:22,236
Then, a few levels later, we start to add other mechanics in with the goats that we've

546
00:30:22,456 --> 00:30:24,117
already kind of introduced before.

547
00:30:24,237 --> 00:30:29,402
So here we've got those falling panels, which I've highlighted in orange, and we've also

548
00:30:29,482 --> 00:30:30,963
got some falling rocks above.

549
00:30:31,584 --> 00:30:33,984
So the falling panels, if the player connects to those,

550
00:30:34,024 --> 00:30:35,405
then they might fall into the goat.

551
00:30:36,085 --> 00:30:38,846
And also if they pull down one of those gray rocks

552
00:30:38,906 --> 00:30:40,946
at the top, that might actually crush the goat.

553
00:30:41,327 --> 00:30:43,527
So we start to teach the player that these

554
00:30:43,567 --> 00:30:48,089
are these other mechanics that layer onto the goats.

555
00:30:49,649 --> 00:30:50,910
Super quick example here.

556
00:30:51,410 --> 00:30:52,910
Player pulls down the rock.

557
00:30:53,110 --> 00:30:54,411
The rock shakes the dynamite.

558
00:30:54,451 --> 00:30:56,491
The dynamite explodes and sends the goat flying.

559
00:30:56,511 --> 00:30:57,311
So.

560
00:31:00,195 --> 00:31:03,596
The next thing that I did relating to mechanics

561
00:31:03,656 --> 00:31:07,618
was I made this diagram, which is basically

562
00:31:07,798 --> 00:31:08,818
every level of the game.

563
00:31:09,799 --> 00:31:13,460
And then it shows what mechanic features in that level.

564
00:31:13,540 --> 00:31:16,562
So that's the colors you can see to the right-hand side.

565
00:31:17,162 --> 00:31:21,844
So the point of this really is to just kind of sanity check,

566
00:31:21,884 --> 00:31:24,945
like, am I using those mechanics to their fullest?

567
00:31:25,385 --> 00:31:26,626
You know, if there's huge gaps.

568
00:31:27,226 --> 00:31:32,073
in this sheet, that means I'm kind of forgetting about a mechanic for a while, right?

569
00:31:33,455 --> 00:31:38,803
So it's about, it's kind of like a reminder just to make sure that you've got an even dispersal of

570
00:31:38,843 --> 00:31:43,289
these mechanics, so you're keeping things fresh and you're not kind of relying on one for too long.

571
00:31:45,031 --> 00:31:49,932
Also, you'll notice this is kind of a curve that is coming in from the top there,

572
00:31:49,972 --> 00:31:53,193
and that's basically the curve of kind of mechanic introduction.

573
00:31:54,113 --> 00:32:01,915
So the reason that is a curve and not a line is because you want to introduce mechanics much faster at the start of the game,

574
00:32:02,435 --> 00:32:06,476
because that is going to provide maximum interest to the player,

575
00:32:06,876 --> 00:32:11,878
so that they're more likely to keep playing because they're basically seeing a lot of new stuff at the beginning of the game.

576
00:32:12,749 --> 00:32:16,253
This is super important for mobile games where people have really short attention spans,

577
00:32:16,453 --> 00:32:17,915
especially if the game is free.

578
00:32:19,276 --> 00:32:21,639
So if it's a free game, they've had no commitment, right?

579
00:32:23,275 --> 00:32:27,337
So next thing to talk about is variety and pacing.

580
00:32:27,457 --> 00:32:30,099
So this was another really important aspect

581
00:32:30,139 --> 00:32:32,741
that I found when making the levels.

582
00:32:33,842 --> 00:32:36,203
So my kind of aim with the levels

583
00:32:36,263 --> 00:32:39,245
was to make sure that there's no single part of the level that

584
00:32:39,285 --> 00:32:42,828
would repeat in the same way later in the level.

585
00:32:43,008 --> 00:32:45,950
So whenever I had some section of gameplay,

586
00:32:45,970 --> 00:32:48,111
I'd make sure that if it was repeated,

587
00:32:49,212 --> 00:32:50,853
it would repeat in a different way.

588
00:32:52,154 --> 00:32:57,357
So also I was trying to vary the spaces of the level.

589
00:32:57,417 --> 00:33:01,820
So we'd have larger spaces where you could fully swing and move quite fast,

590
00:33:02,300 --> 00:33:06,763
and then also have tighter spaces where it was harder to get through and you had to slow down.

591
00:33:07,263 --> 00:33:12,026
And the idea I had was to try and vary between these two styles all the time.

592
00:33:14,767 --> 00:33:19,889
Another thing that I was trying to vary was the difficulty of each level,

593
00:33:20,049 --> 00:33:25,190
so that this would bounce up and down as you played through, i.e. some bits were easier and

594
00:33:25,230 --> 00:33:31,592
some bits were harder, and this would constantly change as you go through. I'll just show a quick

595
00:33:31,652 --> 00:33:37,653
example of that. This is another level of the game quite early on. So this blue line here,

596
00:33:37,713 --> 00:33:39,794
this is kind of the main route through the level.

597
00:33:40,940 --> 00:33:42,301
So yeah, player starts at the bottom,

598
00:33:42,381 --> 00:33:43,722
has to climb all the way to the top.

599
00:33:44,382 --> 00:33:46,423
This is one of the more linear levels, I'd say.

600
00:33:46,984 --> 00:33:49,885
And I've kind of labeled here the areas

601
00:33:49,985 --> 00:33:51,546
which are slow to navigate through,

602
00:33:52,047 --> 00:33:54,308
where there is, say, like an obstacle,

603
00:33:54,388 --> 00:33:55,669
or there's just a narrow gap.

604
00:33:56,429 --> 00:33:57,590
And then there's also some areas

605
00:33:57,630 --> 00:33:59,010
that are faster to navigate through,

606
00:33:59,050 --> 00:34:00,331
where there's more clear space

607
00:34:00,551 --> 00:34:01,772
and more things to grab onto.

608
00:34:02,793 --> 00:34:04,674
And as you can see, this is varying

609
00:34:04,834 --> 00:34:06,154
all the way to the top of the level.

610
00:34:07,650 --> 00:34:12,212
Then I've also labeled up kind of the areas that are harder and easier in the level.

611
00:34:13,373 --> 00:34:16,995
So, you know, the harder bits are the ones where there's maybe a dangerous obstacle.

612
00:34:17,455 --> 00:34:20,097
The easy ones are where there's more things to grapple on to.

613
00:34:21,117 --> 00:34:25,960
And as you can see, again, I'm trying to vary this throughout the level. So you're constantly

614
00:34:26,600 --> 00:34:29,802
kind of getting an easy bit and then a harder bit and then an easier bit.

615
00:34:32,149 --> 00:34:37,935
Another thing I was doing with variety was trying to make sure there was a variety of routes.

616
00:34:39,237 --> 00:34:43,401
So I wanted to make sure there was more than one way for each obstacle.

617
00:34:44,482 --> 00:34:51,029
So this basically meant having a main path through the level, but then lots of optional side paths.

618
00:34:52,310 --> 00:34:56,393
So this is basically, again, thinking about like mobile,

619
00:34:56,453 --> 00:34:58,215
where you've got a very wide audience

620
00:34:58,255 --> 00:35:00,356
and you don't really want someone to get stuck on the game.

621
00:35:00,877 --> 00:35:05,000
So my idea was to kind of make the main map relatively easy,

622
00:35:05,420 --> 00:35:08,983
but then have optional challenge by the pickups,

623
00:35:09,043 --> 00:35:11,264
like the pickups being in harder to reach places.

624
00:35:13,206 --> 00:35:14,006
So yeah, as we were saying,

625
00:35:14,066 --> 00:35:15,427
mobile is a very wide audience,

626
00:35:15,487 --> 00:35:16,708
so you don't want someone to get stuck.

627
00:35:19,128 --> 00:35:20,829
So, quick example of that.

628
00:35:20,909 --> 00:35:23,690
This is the first level where you encounter falling rocks.

629
00:35:25,171 --> 00:35:26,891
So, it's quite a simple level.

630
00:35:27,031 --> 00:35:29,372
You kind of go straight all the way up, really.

631
00:35:29,793 --> 00:35:31,893
The main path I've labeled in blue.

632
00:35:33,754 --> 00:35:36,155
And you can see there's these side paths

633
00:35:36,395 --> 00:35:37,656
in green to the edge there.

634
00:35:38,416 --> 00:35:40,437
So, the player has optional routes they can go.

635
00:35:40,457 --> 00:35:43,878
And those optional routes contain those pickups.

636
00:35:44,398 --> 00:35:45,679
So, they're a little harder to get to.

637
00:35:47,116 --> 00:35:49,497
You'll also notice that there's a few points here,

638
00:35:50,178 --> 00:35:51,399
especially right at the bottom,

639
00:35:51,459 --> 00:35:54,021
where there's almost no way through

640
00:35:54,081 --> 00:35:56,143
without encountering a falling rock, right?

641
00:35:56,203 --> 00:35:58,665
So again, because this was a tutorial level

642
00:35:58,725 --> 00:35:59,586
for the falling rocks,

643
00:35:59,986 --> 00:36:02,988
I was basically forcing the player to experience them.

644
00:36:03,369 --> 00:36:05,010
And if they didn't experience the first one,

645
00:36:05,230 --> 00:36:07,292
they sure as hell would experience one

646
00:36:07,452 --> 00:36:08,493
somewhere else in this level

647
00:36:08,513 --> 00:36:10,194
because it's loaded with falling rocks.

648
00:36:12,925 --> 00:36:14,788
So next thing to talk about is theming.

649
00:36:16,069 --> 00:36:20,855
So one thing that I realized was really important in making the levels was

650
00:36:21,376 --> 00:36:26,503
to try and find at least one unique and memorable element in every level.

651
00:36:28,385 --> 00:36:33,810
So this could be something where there's a very unique use of a mechanic,

652
00:36:34,411 --> 00:36:39,636
or it could even be something that the shape of the level is very different.

653
00:36:40,517 --> 00:36:46,163
So the point is, you're basically trying to make something where you're answering the question,

654
00:36:46,444 --> 00:36:48,846
why does this level exist in the game, right?

655
00:36:49,487 --> 00:36:51,689
Is there another level that's almost the same?

656
00:36:51,910 --> 00:36:54,092
Then it probably shouldn't exist, right?

657
00:36:54,152 --> 00:36:57,516
Does it add anything new to the current set of levels that I have?

658
00:36:59,630 --> 00:37:03,071
So another way to think about it is imagine two people

659
00:37:03,091 --> 00:37:05,511
that have played the game talking to each other.

660
00:37:05,971 --> 00:37:09,472
Like, can they describe the level to their friend

661
00:37:10,132 --> 00:37:12,053
without telling them the name of the level

662
00:37:12,073 --> 00:37:13,193
or the number of it, you know?

663
00:37:13,513 --> 00:37:14,854
They'd be like, this is the level

664
00:37:14,934 --> 00:37:17,194
with the giant octopus or whatever.

665
00:37:17,914 --> 00:37:20,735
So this was kind of what I was trying to go for

666
00:37:20,795 --> 00:37:22,516
and something that I found really important.

667
00:37:23,676 --> 00:37:25,796
So let's show a few examples of that.

668
00:37:27,554 --> 00:37:30,516
So this level is actually called Leap of Faith,

669
00:37:30,796 --> 00:37:33,198
and you'll notice there's this bit in the middle there

670
00:37:33,458 --> 00:37:36,780
where the only way to get from this lower part

671
00:37:36,800 --> 00:37:37,941
of the mountain where you start

672
00:37:38,581 --> 00:37:40,463
onto that larger upper part

673
00:37:40,943 --> 00:37:45,566
is by grappling a stalactite that can fall.

674
00:37:46,046 --> 00:37:47,828
And it's literally the only thing you can grapple.

675
00:37:47,968 --> 00:37:49,189
And then after you grapple that,

676
00:37:49,229 --> 00:37:51,210
you really need to quickly grapple the other ones.

677
00:37:52,030 --> 00:37:53,732
So it's kind of like, yeah, it's basically a leap of faith,

678
00:37:53,772 --> 00:37:56,173
and it's quite a memorable moment in this level.

679
00:37:57,957 --> 00:38:03,849
So another thing that makes this level quite memorable is that it also kind of looks like Dr. Zoidberg.

680
00:38:08,396 --> 00:38:12,717
So I'm just going to show you quickly now that level that you saw earlier in the game.

681
00:38:12,817 --> 00:38:18,098
So this was another level where I wanted to make this feel very unique.

682
00:38:18,618 --> 00:38:22,039
So I kind of, yeah, basically stole this idea from Indiana Jones, right?

683
00:38:22,399 --> 00:38:23,999
Where you've got this giant falling boulder.

684
00:38:24,419 --> 00:38:27,900
And this is like the kind of the largest rock the player has seen at that point.

685
00:38:27,960 --> 00:38:29,600
And there's like no way to avoid it.

686
00:38:31,021 --> 00:38:32,701
So this made this made the level very memorable.

687
00:38:32,721 --> 00:38:33,861
So...

688
00:38:35,699 --> 00:38:40,083
Just to kind of explain how I managed

689
00:38:40,123 --> 00:38:42,526
to kind of keep this idea of theming in my mind

690
00:38:42,566 --> 00:38:45,909
when I'm designing levels is what you see here

691
00:38:45,969 --> 00:38:49,673
are two diagrams that I've drawn on paper.

692
00:38:49,753 --> 00:38:51,715
And they're just A4 sheets, right?

693
00:38:51,755 --> 00:38:53,276
So this is quite a, each one of those

694
00:38:53,497 --> 00:38:55,258
is a relatively small piece of paper.

695
00:38:55,899 --> 00:38:58,802
And you can see I've crammed in like about, you know,

696
00:38:59,562 --> 00:39:04,284
six diagrams of an entire level into each kind of corner.

697
00:39:04,444 --> 00:39:07,045
And the reason for that was to force myself

698
00:39:07,125 --> 00:39:09,866
to not get too detailed with each level

699
00:39:09,986 --> 00:39:11,607
and instead draw out like,

700
00:39:11,847 --> 00:39:13,708
what is the unique thing about this level?

701
00:39:13,808 --> 00:39:15,828
Like, how is it different to the other levels?

702
00:39:16,649 --> 00:39:18,489
And by drawing super small,

703
00:39:18,890 --> 00:39:20,510
I couldn't get focused on any details.

704
00:39:20,550 --> 00:39:21,831
I had to literally think, okay,

705
00:39:21,951 --> 00:39:23,631
how to set this level apart,

706
00:39:23,691 --> 00:39:26,853
both in terms of its shape or through creating,

707
00:39:26,893 --> 00:39:28,713
you know, a unique element in there.

708
00:39:30,329 --> 00:39:37,351
Um, so another super important thing, um, that I'm going to mention just briefly is playtesting.

709
00:39:38,052 --> 00:39:46,755
Um, so I literally gave this game to everyone to play, like my nephews, my friends, my mom, my dad.

710
00:39:47,576 --> 00:39:49,877
You can see my mom there actually in the bottom left corner.

711
00:39:50,498 --> 00:39:52,299
She was a particularly useful play tester

712
00:39:52,319 --> 00:39:55,101
because you can see the kind of claw grip she had on the mouse

713
00:39:55,141 --> 00:39:59,944
was quite unique and meant that she had almost no control over the player characters.

714
00:39:59,964 --> 00:40:05,507
So if my mom could beat a level, then that proved that it was safe for human consumption.

715
00:40:06,768 --> 00:40:10,050
So, yeah, getting your game in front of people is mega important,

716
00:40:10,171 --> 00:40:13,733
not just because it's going to help you see a load of bugs that you wouldn't notice,

717
00:40:14,253 --> 00:40:14,934
but it's also...

718
00:40:16,675 --> 00:40:18,656
It's going to help you just feel better about the game

719
00:40:18,696 --> 00:40:20,497
and realize there's people enjoying it.

720
00:40:22,158 --> 00:40:23,658
So super-duper important.

721
00:40:25,860 --> 00:40:28,221
And also, if you've got your game on mobile,

722
00:40:28,261 --> 00:40:30,942
this is a mega big advantage because you can just literally

723
00:40:30,982 --> 00:40:31,803
whip it out your pocket.

724
00:40:31,823 --> 00:40:34,004
You've got it on you all the time.

725
00:40:34,104 --> 00:40:36,825
So anyone you meet, you can just say, hey, I'm making a game.

726
00:40:36,965 --> 00:40:38,826
Want to play it?

727
00:40:39,126 --> 00:40:39,907
So that's really useful.

728
00:40:41,408 --> 00:40:41,748
All right.

729
00:40:41,848 --> 00:40:43,669
So at this point, I was six months in.

730
00:40:44,570 --> 00:40:45,891
I had all the game mechanics.

731
00:40:46,651 --> 00:40:48,451
I'd figured out how to make good levels.

732
00:40:49,772 --> 00:40:51,712
I'd close to final the environment art.

733
00:40:53,352 --> 00:40:54,293
I was almost done, right?

734
00:40:55,633 --> 00:40:59,814
So I want to ask you guys if anyone can guess how long it

735
00:40:59,854 --> 00:41:03,175
took me at this point to launch the game.

736
00:41:03,855 --> 00:41:05,735
Just shout out anything you can think of.

737
00:41:10,423 --> 00:41:11,583
Most of you are actually right.

738
00:41:11,603 --> 00:41:12,703
I thought you were going to guess less,

739
00:41:12,803 --> 00:41:14,984
but yes, it was one whole year.

740
00:41:15,064 --> 00:41:18,125
So original idea of three to six months,

741
00:41:18,325 --> 00:41:20,985
yeah, that was completely not happening at this point.

742
00:41:22,326 --> 00:41:24,486
So yeah, like the reason it took so long

743
00:41:24,506 --> 00:41:26,727
was I still had UI to build,

744
00:41:28,027 --> 00:41:29,928
a whole progression system and economy.

745
00:41:31,230 --> 00:41:38,304
All this ads and monetization stuff, marketing, like, yeah, this was a huge challenge.

746
00:41:38,524 --> 00:41:41,891
And also because these tests are like super boring.

747
00:41:44,244 --> 00:41:46,205
Seriously, if you ever have to deal with, like,

748
00:41:46,485 --> 00:41:50,448
ad mediation networks and monetization stuff,

749
00:41:50,548 --> 00:41:51,429
it is, yeah.

750
00:41:52,350 --> 00:41:53,991
This is not the indie dream, let's say.

751
00:41:54,791 --> 00:41:56,893
So anyway, at this point in the project,

752
00:41:56,953 --> 00:41:58,194
I was getting really anxious.

753
00:41:58,794 --> 00:42:01,376
I had a lot of friends asking me throughout the project,

754
00:42:01,396 --> 00:42:02,777
like, oh, you're working on that game, yeah.

755
00:42:03,498 --> 00:42:05,619
How long is it gonna take you to finish that?

756
00:42:05,739 --> 00:42:07,841
And I was always like, yeah, about three months maybe.

757
00:42:08,702 --> 00:42:10,542
And then it asked me three months later, like,

758
00:42:10,882 --> 00:42:12,503
yes, so have you finished yet?

759
00:42:12,583 --> 00:42:14,263
Oh, no, it took about like maybe three more months.

760
00:42:14,303 --> 00:42:17,464
And this would happen every time and became like this running joke.

761
00:42:18,244 --> 00:42:19,925
And I was getting really worried, to be honest.

762
00:42:19,965 --> 00:42:22,706
Like I was thinking, am I actually going to be able to balance

763
00:42:22,746 --> 00:42:23,786
the progression of this game?

764
00:42:23,926 --> 00:42:26,167
All this economy stuff, it was super difficult.

765
00:42:26,927 --> 00:42:29,848
Am I going to finish before I like I run out of money?

766
00:42:29,868 --> 00:42:32,348
And is this even going to be successful?

767
00:42:34,120 --> 00:42:35,221
Am I wasting my time?

768
00:42:36,421 --> 00:42:38,183
These are the kind of thoughts that you have

769
00:42:38,803 --> 00:42:41,045
when you are literally the only team member

770
00:42:41,725 --> 00:42:44,808
and you're building this thing by yourself.

771
00:42:46,249 --> 00:42:47,830
I asked a lot of people for advice,

772
00:42:48,951 --> 00:42:50,432
like kind of professionals in the industry,

773
00:42:50,532 --> 00:42:52,814
and to be honest, most people said,

774
00:42:53,174 --> 00:42:54,875
just get the game out as soon as you can.

775
00:42:55,396 --> 00:42:57,037
It's probably going to fail anyway.

776
00:42:57,817 --> 00:42:59,759
And this was not terribly helpful.

777
00:42:59,879 --> 00:43:03,961
It's very sound advice, but it is not that helpful.

778
00:43:04,862 --> 00:43:07,683
So basically, I was kind of gambling.

779
00:43:07,904 --> 00:43:09,825
I was putting more chips on the table.

780
00:43:09,865 --> 00:43:11,826
But the longer I spent on the game

781
00:43:11,886 --> 00:43:14,347
and the more things I was adding to it to try and make it

782
00:43:14,387 --> 00:43:17,009
better, it's basically like gambling.

783
00:43:17,049 --> 00:43:18,770
It's putting bigger and bigger bets

784
00:43:19,571 --> 00:43:21,412
in the hope of success and return.

785
00:43:22,537 --> 00:43:24,078
And to be honest, even at this point,

786
00:43:24,719 --> 00:43:26,800
even Grimlock's wise words were not helping,

787
00:43:26,880 --> 00:43:31,062
because I was just feeling like, this is really scary.

788
00:43:31,102 --> 00:43:33,104
Like, I'm really running out of money,

789
00:43:33,484 --> 00:43:35,585
and it's just taking too long.

790
00:43:35,885 --> 00:43:38,147
And it was actually a friend of mine,

791
00:43:38,187 --> 00:43:40,228
actually the guy that I'd previously emailed,

792
00:43:40,428 --> 00:43:42,429
and he'd told me he really loved goats,

793
00:43:42,809 --> 00:43:43,610
wanted goats in the game.

794
00:43:44,670 --> 00:43:45,971
It was him that kind of,

795
00:43:46,692 --> 00:43:48,072
Yeah, gave me some advice.

796
00:43:48,433 --> 00:43:52,215
Basically, he was telling me like he'd worked

797
00:43:52,275 --> 00:43:53,876
as a writer for a very long time,

798
00:43:54,736 --> 00:43:57,318
where he was kind of working at home and working by himself,

799
00:43:57,998 --> 00:43:59,979
whereas previously he'd worked with other people.

800
00:44:00,760 --> 00:44:02,961
And yeah, I'm kind of butchering the quote.

801
00:44:03,061 --> 00:44:04,542
I mean, it's Spanish anyway,

802
00:44:04,562 --> 00:44:05,562
and I think he told me in Spanish,

803
00:44:05,602 --> 00:44:08,104
but basically he was saying that like,

804
00:44:08,724 --> 00:44:11,205
When you're working by yourself, you're not doing meetings,

805
00:44:12,086 --> 00:44:13,367
you're not talking to other people,

806
00:44:13,407 --> 00:44:16,088
you're not got distractions, you are solidly working

807
00:44:16,768 --> 00:44:19,390
and you are solidly improving your skills.

808
00:44:20,030 --> 00:44:21,771
So basically you're getting a lot better

809
00:44:21,811 --> 00:44:22,531
at what you're doing.

810
00:44:23,392 --> 00:44:25,353
And so this was really helpful to me

811
00:44:25,373 --> 00:44:26,333
because I thought to myself,

812
00:44:26,353 --> 00:44:28,514
well, even if I completely screw this up,

813
00:44:29,375 --> 00:44:31,576
at least I'm gonna be better at making games.

814
00:44:32,156 --> 00:44:34,597
And this was kind of what I needed to keep going

815
00:44:34,738 --> 00:44:36,158
and to actually get to the end.

816
00:44:37,527 --> 00:44:40,550
So this leads us to part four, the launch of the game,

817
00:44:40,830 --> 00:44:42,492
but not the actual launch.

818
00:44:43,173 --> 00:44:44,354
This was the soft launch.

819
00:44:44,434 --> 00:44:46,176
This was one and a half years in.

820
00:44:46,236 --> 00:44:49,540
I finally got to actually soft launch.

821
00:44:49,600 --> 00:44:52,683
But of course, you know, the reason I chose to soft launch

822
00:44:52,723 --> 00:44:54,746
is because there was still a few more things to do in the game.

823
00:44:54,886 --> 00:44:57,589
And also, I was terrified of doing a full launch

824
00:44:57,629 --> 00:44:59,050
in case it was a complete failure.

825
00:45:00,611 --> 00:45:03,953
So I used to compete to get a few installs for free.

826
00:45:05,813 --> 00:45:07,094
I soft launched the game in India,

827
00:45:07,814 --> 00:45:10,495
basically because it was super cheap user acquisition.

828
00:45:11,576 --> 00:45:13,577
And this is the stats here.

829
00:45:13,597 --> 00:45:15,958
You can see the number of users on the Y axis,

830
00:45:16,338 --> 00:45:17,918
and then there's time on the X axis.

831
00:45:18,519 --> 00:45:19,599
This was something like, I don't know,

832
00:45:19,659 --> 00:45:21,720
five days after soft launch.

833
00:45:22,100 --> 00:45:24,101
And you can see there's about 300 users there.

834
00:45:24,141 --> 00:45:27,062
So, okay, this is useful when you get some data from that, right?

835
00:45:28,443 --> 00:45:28,783
And then...

836
00:45:30,531 --> 00:45:34,735
Next day, suddenly, there was a huge bump in users.

837
00:45:35,616 --> 00:45:37,178
But when I was looking at the stats,

838
00:45:37,678 --> 00:45:41,963
I was reading still 300 users in the Unity telemetry,

839
00:45:41,983 --> 00:45:46,187
and yet there was 3,000 users in the Google telemetry.

840
00:45:46,207 --> 00:45:48,209
Like, what's going on here?

841
00:45:48,670 --> 00:45:50,211
And I was like, okay, let's just have a look.

842
00:45:50,231 --> 00:45:51,933
Where are these users coming from, right?

843
00:45:52,013 --> 00:45:52,934
It should be India, right?

844
00:45:53,969 --> 00:45:55,590
Nope, it was Russia.

845
00:45:55,610 --> 00:45:57,871
I was like, why, how?

846
00:45:57,991 --> 00:45:59,591
The game isn't released in Russia.

847
00:45:59,651 --> 00:45:59,871
What?

848
00:46:01,972 --> 00:46:04,493
Oh, that's what's happened.

849
00:46:04,993 --> 00:46:07,414
So yeah, basically the game got pirated.

850
00:46:09,115 --> 00:46:12,756
And then if we return to the graph, a few days later,

851
00:46:12,936 --> 00:46:14,737
so I've scaled the graph down here

852
00:46:14,797 --> 00:46:16,737
so that you can see it's 3,000 users

853
00:46:16,797 --> 00:46:19,018
at the top of that little red curve there.

854
00:46:19,058 --> 00:46:20,799
And I think you can guess what's gonna happen next.

855
00:46:22,078 --> 00:46:23,959
Boom, within a few more days,

856
00:46:24,200 --> 00:46:26,121
suddenly there were 300,000 users.

857
00:46:26,582 --> 00:46:31,646
And this time it was not Russia, it was China.

858
00:46:33,348 --> 00:46:34,649
So basically after two weeks,

859
00:46:34,669 --> 00:46:35,389
I got 500,000 illegal downloads.

860
00:46:35,810 --> 00:46:36,130
And then...

861
00:46:41,213 --> 00:46:44,055
Suddenly I get this email from this company called Yodo One,

862
00:46:44,095 --> 00:46:44,575
and they're like,

863
00:46:45,016 --> 00:46:47,538
hey, we've been playing your game and we really like it.

864
00:46:48,719 --> 00:46:49,939
Do you want to have a conversation?

865
00:46:50,019 --> 00:46:51,601
I'm like, well, that's interesting you're playing my game

866
00:46:51,621 --> 00:46:53,322
because it's not actually released in China.

867
00:46:53,682 --> 00:46:55,984
They're like, yeah, we found it on this site.

868
00:46:56,144 --> 00:46:57,845
And yeah, anyway, we want to talk to you

869
00:46:57,865 --> 00:46:59,747
about a possible publishing deal.

870
00:47:00,599 --> 00:47:02,920
My, okay, sure, I'll have a chat.

871
00:47:02,960 --> 00:47:04,980
Now, I actually knew about Yoda One

872
00:47:05,040 --> 00:47:07,521
because they'd worked on Crossy Road, which was huge.

873
00:47:07,921 --> 00:47:09,161
I think they'd done the Android version.

874
00:47:10,041 --> 00:47:12,582
They'd also worked on a game called Rodeo Stampede,

875
00:47:12,622 --> 00:47:14,122
and they were the publisher worldwide.

876
00:47:15,003 --> 00:47:15,983
And they were telling me about this,

877
00:47:16,023 --> 00:47:17,103
you know, when I chatted to them.

878
00:47:17,123 --> 00:47:18,783
And they were like, yeah, I think your game

879
00:47:18,843 --> 00:47:20,964
can be as big as Rodeo Stampede.

880
00:47:21,224 --> 00:47:23,545
You know, we only take on a couple of games per year.

881
00:47:24,666 --> 00:47:26,507
And, yeah, we think your game could be

882
00:47:26,888 --> 00:47:27,928
as successful as that game.

883
00:47:28,589 --> 00:47:31,491
So, okay, let's have a little look how this game is doing.

884
00:47:31,591 --> 00:47:34,173
And like, Rodeo Stampede at that point

885
00:47:34,233 --> 00:47:35,534
had 120 million downloads.

886
00:47:36,135 --> 00:47:39,377
And using my very basic maths of divide by a million

887
00:47:39,417 --> 00:47:42,459
downloads to get the amount of money the gamers made,

888
00:47:42,499 --> 00:47:44,080
which I'm sure is massively accurate,

889
00:47:44,921 --> 00:47:45,782
you get $12 million.

890
00:47:46,002 --> 00:47:46,402
$12 million.

891
00:47:52,969 --> 00:47:56,330
So yeah, anyway, basically I was like,

892
00:47:56,730 --> 00:47:59,171
okay, let's try and do some kind of deal.

893
00:47:59,711 --> 00:48:01,232
And I managed to negotiate something

894
00:48:01,252 --> 00:48:04,333
where I got quite a large upfront sum

895
00:48:04,453 --> 00:48:06,514
for kind of licensing the game to them,

896
00:48:06,674 --> 00:48:08,235
i.e. allowing them to be my publisher

897
00:48:08,315 --> 00:48:09,916
and then for us to work on the game

898
00:48:09,956 --> 00:48:10,876
and make some improvements.

899
00:48:12,317 --> 00:48:16,158
And this basically took a lot of pressure off me

900
00:48:16,198 --> 00:48:18,259
because it kind of meant that even if the game

901
00:48:18,299 --> 00:48:19,340
kind of didn't do that well,

902
00:48:19,380 --> 00:48:21,221
I'd still have some security there.

903
00:48:22,602 --> 00:48:26,145
So, they invited me to China to work on the game with them.

904
00:48:26,165 --> 00:48:28,527
They wanted to make some improvements to the progression system.

905
00:48:29,288 --> 00:48:34,653
This was amazing because I really liked dumplings and I got to eat as many as I wanted.

906
00:48:34,813 --> 00:48:37,575
And then, yeah, we worked on the game for a while.

907
00:48:38,576 --> 00:48:42,358
And yeah, so now I'm going to ask you guys one more time.

908
00:48:42,478 --> 00:48:46,019
So at this point, after getting a publisher, bear in mind,

909
00:48:46,099 --> 00:48:50,801
they put a team of 10 people on the game to work with me, right?

910
00:48:51,061 --> 00:48:54,163
That's 10 times the original team size.

911
00:48:54,663 --> 00:48:59,225
How long do you guys think it took to finish from this point to the end?

912
00:49:01,462 --> 00:49:03,263
Wow, you guys are super pessimistic.

913
00:49:03,303 --> 00:49:04,904
Okay, it took a whole year,

914
00:49:05,865 --> 00:49:07,926
which is a pretty long time, right?

915
00:49:08,686 --> 00:49:11,407
Anyway, so two and a half years later,

916
00:49:12,028 --> 00:49:13,949
finally, the game was released.

917
00:49:15,209 --> 00:49:17,471
This is a few little gifs here from the final game.

918
00:49:19,872 --> 00:49:23,814
So, yeah, so how did it do?

919
00:49:24,855 --> 00:49:26,996
Well, it got a feature with Apple and Google,

920
00:49:27,596 --> 00:49:28,496
so that was really cool.

921
00:49:29,437 --> 00:49:30,858
It did not set the world on fire.

922
00:49:32,120 --> 00:49:35,003
I did not become a millionaire, I am sorry to say.

923
00:49:36,424 --> 00:49:40,468
But it got over 2 million downloads on the Apple Store,

924
00:49:41,309 --> 00:49:42,530
over 2 million on Google Play.

925
00:49:43,972 --> 00:49:46,274
It recuperated all the opportunity costs and more

926
00:49:46,314 --> 00:49:49,597
for me, and it still has players.

927
00:49:49,838 --> 00:49:53,621
So basically, for a solo indie developer, it was a success.

928
00:49:56,195 --> 00:49:57,196
So let's sum up now.

929
00:49:58,556 --> 00:50:00,677
So when I was working on the game,

930
00:50:01,517 --> 00:50:04,998
I used a tool called Toggle, which tracks how much time

931
00:50:05,018 --> 00:50:06,019
you spend on a task.

932
00:50:06,719 --> 00:50:09,180
So basically, when you start a task, you start this timer.

933
00:50:10,040 --> 00:50:12,180
When you work for it for a few hours,

934
00:50:12,301 --> 00:50:14,421
then you finish the task, you stop the timer,

935
00:50:14,481 --> 00:50:15,862
and you write, this is what I worked on.

936
00:50:16,202 --> 00:50:16,982
It's in this category.

937
00:50:17,662 --> 00:50:20,245
Then at the end of the project, you can get a nice little graph like this,

938
00:50:20,365 --> 00:50:22,287
and it tells you how long you spent on everything.

939
00:50:23,369 --> 00:50:26,412
So even though this game took a very long time to make,

940
00:50:27,153 --> 00:50:30,657
you can see level design is only 9% of that time.

941
00:50:30,677 --> 00:50:36,143
And if you think about it, this is like literally level design, level building, level testing, and all that business.

942
00:50:36,643 --> 00:50:38,805
Like, I think 9% is actually quite small.

943
00:50:39,546 --> 00:50:41,487
And so, and I think a huge part of this

944
00:50:41,527 --> 00:50:44,349
was because I have this process of, you know,

945
00:50:44,429 --> 00:50:46,691
using this editor, this custom bit editor,

946
00:50:47,031 --> 00:50:48,953
to allow me to rapidly build levels.

947
00:50:51,254 --> 00:50:53,336
So, here's some key takeaways.

948
00:50:55,552 --> 00:51:02,140
So, yeah, I highly recommend if you're working as an indie dev to make a level design process

949
00:51:02,180 --> 00:51:07,267
or a level building process that allows you to rapidly iterate, because this is going

950
00:51:07,287 --> 00:51:12,092
to help you to not only build levels quickly initially, but also change them later if you

951
00:51:12,132 --> 00:51:14,355
need to, to either fix bugs or make them work better.

952
00:51:15,748 --> 00:51:20,229
I highly recommend theming your levels around at least one memorable aspect

953
00:51:20,589 --> 00:51:26,050
so that the levels, you know, players can remember them after they played them

954
00:51:26,810 --> 00:51:27,830
and they feel more unique.

955
00:51:28,990 --> 00:51:31,331
I'd also recommend layering your game systems

956
00:51:31,951 --> 00:51:36,072
so that they interplay with each other to create maximum variety out of,

957
00:51:36,292 --> 00:51:38,092
you know, as few mechanics as possible.

958
00:51:39,833 --> 00:51:42,353
I'd also recommend using other people's code wherever possible

959
00:51:43,393 --> 00:51:44,053
and adding goats.

960
00:51:45,608 --> 00:51:51,233
But yeah, basically, you want to try to follow your own unique path to success as an indie developer.

961
00:51:51,934 --> 00:51:54,015
Because, yeah, it's a very personal journey.

962
00:51:55,016 --> 00:51:59,460
You're going to have your own advantages that you can bring to that,

963
00:51:59,480 --> 00:52:01,982
but also you're going to have your own disadvantages,

964
00:52:02,042 --> 00:52:06,125
and your personality is a massive part of making a game by yourself.

965
00:52:06,966 --> 00:52:12,449
And as I was saying, my personality was basically worrying about things and worrying, like,

966
00:52:12,629 --> 00:52:13,430
is this going to work?

967
00:52:13,510 --> 00:52:19,073
And so I needed to overcome that by basically being a bit more stupid and not judging myself

968
00:52:19,113 --> 00:52:19,454
too much.

969
00:52:21,035 --> 00:52:24,837
So, yeah, just quickly, you might wonder, like, what am I working on next?

970
00:52:25,898 --> 00:52:27,179
Makes sense to do a sequel, right?

971
00:52:27,319 --> 00:52:29,800
Or possibly another climbing game, another mobile game.

972
00:52:31,144 --> 00:52:34,646
Actually, no, I'm working on an action horror roguelike

973
00:52:35,307 --> 00:52:38,929
about a rapidly expanding, procedurally growing tentacle

974
00:52:38,949 --> 00:52:39,350
monster.

975
00:52:39,850 --> 00:52:42,893
And this game is way more ambitious than Hang Life.

976
00:52:43,273 --> 00:52:45,094
I'm still doing it mostly by myself.

977
00:52:46,956 --> 00:52:49,898
So yeah, why am I working on such a huge project?

978
00:52:50,839 --> 00:52:52,639
I'm being stupid.

979
00:52:53,040 --> 00:52:55,181
Too stupid to fail.

980
00:52:55,981 --> 00:52:57,502
So yeah, that's the end of my talk.

981
00:52:57,922 --> 00:53:00,503
If you want to keep in touch, yeah,

982
00:53:00,583 --> 00:53:01,904
there's actually a lot more details

983
00:53:02,024 --> 00:53:03,705
on how I built the game.

984
00:53:03,765 --> 00:53:05,826
If you go to this link on Game Developer,

985
00:53:06,746 --> 00:53:08,907
there's free articles or more explaining

986
00:53:09,008 --> 00:53:10,268
much more detail on the process.

